---
description: Security, multi-tenancy, and compliance rules for SalesIQ
alwaysApply: true
---

Security rules:
- Never hardcode secrets, API keys, tokens, credentials, or private URLs (Twilio, OpenAI, AWS, JWT secret, DB password).
- All secrets must be loaded via `app/config.py` using `pydantic-settings` from environment variables or AWS Secrets Manager.
- Never log passwords, JWT tokens, raw API keys, or sensitive user content (call audio, transcript text).
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs — never trust request body, query params, or headers blindly.
- Treat webhook payloads (Twilio, outbound webhooks) as untrusted — validate signatures before processing.
- Enforce authentication on all protected resources — use FastAPI `Depends(get_current_user)`.
- Enforce authorization at the service layer — check `tenant_id` and `role` before acting on resources.
- Use least-privilege access patterns; rate limit sensitive or expensive endpoints.

Multi-tenancy security (critical):
- Every authenticated request must carry a `tenant_id` extracted from the JWT — never from the request body.
- Every database query on tenant-scoped data must filter by `tenant_id` — see `30-database-sqlalchemy.mdc`.
- Never allow cross-tenant data access — if a resource's `tenant_id` does not match the caller's `tenant_id`, return 403.
- Tenant slugs and IDs must not be guessable or predictable — use UUIDs.
- Redis pub/sub channels must be namespaced per tenant to prevent cross-tenant event leakage.

RBAC rules:
- Roles: `super_admin`, `tenant_admin`, `manager`, `agent`.
- `super_admin`: system-level access only (not tenant-scoped operations).
- `tenant_admin`: full access within their tenant.
- `manager`: read analytics, manage agents and leads, view all calls within tenant.
- `agent`: access only their own assigned leads and calls.
- Role checks must be enforced in `core/permissions.py` via FastAPI dependencies — not in route handlers.

JWT and auth rules:
- Access tokens: short TTL (30 minutes default, configurable).
- Refresh tokens: longer TTL (7 days default, configurable), stored server-side or validated with a rotation strategy.
- JWT secret must be long (256-bit+) and rotated periodically — never the default "secret".
- Verify JWT signature and expiry on every protected request.
- On token refresh, invalidate the old refresh token.

Call recording and PII:
- Call recordings contain PII (voice audio) — store only in S3 with server-side encryption.
- Never serve raw Twilio recording URLs — always generate short-lived presigned S3 URLs.
- Transcripts may contain PII — do not log transcript text; mask in log pipelines if needed.
- Consider GDPR compliance: support data export and deletion per-tenant on request.

Audit logging:
- Log all sensitive admin actions in the `audit_logs` table: `action`, `entity_type`, `entity_id`, `user_id`, `tenant_id`, `ip_address`, `changes` (before/after JSONB snapshot).
- Audit logs must be immutable — never update or delete audit log records.
- Covered actions: lead.created, lead.deleted, agent.deactivated, tenant.settings_changed, api_key.created, webhook.created.

AI-specific security:
- Validate GPT-4o structured JSON output before using it to update database records.
- Do not pass raw user-submitted content directly into AI prompts without sanitization (prompt injection risk).
- Protect system prompt templates — do not expose them via API responses.
- Twilio webhook signature validation must be implemented in `app/api/v1/twilio_webhooks.py`.

Infra security:
- Prefer AWS Secrets Manager for production secrets; `.env` file for local development only.
- S3 buckets for recordings must have `BlockPublicAccess` enabled; access via presigned URLs only.
- Do not expose internal FastAPI error detail (`debug=True`) in production.
- Use CORS restrictions — only allow `APP_CORS_ORIGINS` from `app/config.py`.

Do not:
- Assume client-side validation is sufficient — always validate server-side.
- Return internal stack traces or exception details to API clients.
- Trust LLM output in critical flows (deal status changes, billing) without Pydantic validation.
- Commit `.env` files or any file containing secrets to the repository.
